#3 Acute on chronic systolic congestive heart failure
#6 Paroxysmal atrial flutter with variable block.
#11 History of small cell lung cancer s/p resection and radiation, previous treated for radiation pneumonitis
#12 Recurrent squamous cell carcinoma of the right vocal cord status post excision and radiation therapy
#13 Bladder cancer status post resection and BCG treatment in 2003

Mr. Blue is an 87 year old gentleman with a past medical history of COPD, CHF, CAD, atrial flutter, CKD, and history of multiple cancers, who presented to the SMH emergency department with worsening shortness of breath and cough for a few days. He reported that his health has declined gradually over the last month, and he has been using an increasing amount of supplemental oxygen during the day.

In the emergency department, his labs showed Hbg: 12.9; WBC: 12.7; PLT: 203; Na: 140; K: 4.3; chloride: 100; bicarb: 31; BUN: 20; creatinine: 1.6; BNP: 7354. EKG: atrial fibrillation. Chest x-ray reveals pulmonary venous hypertension with perihilar and lower lung edema. Small right effusion. He was given levofloxacin, IV methylprednisolone, and DuoNebs, and he was admitted to the Medicine 1 Service for additional management.

While admitted, he was treated for an acute COPD exacerbation with PO prednisone and PO levofloxacin and for acute on chronic systolic congestive heart failure with IV furosemide. He improved clinically and was transitioned back to his home dose of furosemide. He will be discharge home with supplemental oxygen and prescriptions to finish a 5 day course of prednisone and levofloxacin.

He was seen by physical therapy, and they recommended that Mr. Blue have assistance with all mobility. In discussions with Mr. Blue and his family, they agreed that returning home with home health and physical therapy would be the best option. Risks and benefits of returning home versus placement in a SNF were discussed.
Take a copy of this dismissal summary to your appointment(s).
* Avoid bananas until potassium returns to normal.
- Take an additional 20 mg Lasix if weight is increased 2 pounds over 2 days or 5 pounds over 5 days
- Do not take Lasix if weight is 3 pounds less over two days.
* Follow-up with primary care physician with in one week. With a check of creatinine and potassium.

You may have outpatient appointments at Mayo Clinic that changed during your hospitalization. Refer to your Mayo Clinic Patient Appointment Guide (PAG) for the most current schedule of appointments and detailed instructions of tests/procedures.
Call 507-284-4773, if you did not receive a PAG or need to CANCEL any Mayo Clinic appointment(s).

COGNITIVE SCREEN: Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA) The Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA) is a screen instrument for mild cognitive dysfunction. The following domains are screened: attention and concentration, executive functions, memory, language, visuoconstructional skills, conceptual thinking, calculations, and orientation.
Patient scored 16 out of 30. A score of 26 or greater is considered normal.
Per the MoCA screen, the patient's strengths were visuoconstructional skills, orientation.
Per the MOCA screen, the patient's challenge areas were attention and concentration, executive functions , memory, language, conceptual thinking, calculations.
